WEBVTT

00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:06.320
and Ritz is going to talk about gt4tables. Welcome, Ritz.

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:14.240
Hi, thanks for having me. So I just want to talk about, it's been a good year, 2023 for gt,

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:19.920
two big releases. I just want to take 10 minutes to talk about the new features.

00:00:20.639 --> 00:00:24.799
So this talk is called improvements made to gt in 2023.

00:00:24.799 --> 00:00:32.560
So if you don't know the gt package, it just lets you create tables for publication with a

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:37.040
kind of like a declarative interface. It allows you to fine-tune the appearance of the final

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:42.880
table. We can integrate these tables in publishing workflows like R Markdown,

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:46.639
Cordo, and you can even use these tables in shiny apps.

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:53.919
Let me just show you a bit about how it works with a small overview. So if you don't know gt,

00:00:53.919 --> 00:01:00.480
what you do is you have a data frame, introduce it to gt in pretty much the right form you wanted,

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:07.199
close to the final form of the actual table that you want to see, and then use functions

00:01:07.199 --> 00:01:13.519
to iteratively modify that table. So you introduce a data frame or table to the gt function,

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:19.519
and then use any number of like statements using the functions available in the package.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:24.879
And usually what it can do is you can express these statements in pretty much any order,

00:01:25.519 --> 00:01:30.720
more or less. And what these functions do is they're a bit lazy. They act as instructions,

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:34.720
and gt will then take all those instructions and then figure out what to render.

00:01:36.879 --> 00:01:42.639
So in this little bit of code here, it doesn't have to change depending on the output of the

00:01:42.639 --> 00:01:52.559
table you want. So gt supports HTML, LaTeX, RTF, and that's all for you, and Word. And you don't

00:01:52.559 --> 00:01:57.199
have to change this. You don't have to specify the type of output. Just based on the context,

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.519
you know, it knows that it's in a Word environment or it wants to publish as RTF.

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:07.440
Although you can force it to emit like the text of that if you need that.

00:02:08.399 --> 00:02:15.520
So yeah, it should always work. Use it in Cordo or R Markdown, and you have LaTeX

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:19.919
or PDF defined, it will use the LaTeX output format.

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:27.839
Okay, one thing we really focused on a lot in gt, and this is part of the updates as well,

00:02:28.559 --> 00:02:34.320
is lots of useful formatting functions for cell values. So any numbers you have in a gt table,

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:39.919
in cells in a column, you can format them with tons of these formatting functions.

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:46.559
Even things like dates and times can be formatted, durations. You can create images

00:02:46.559 --> 00:02:53.919
just from addresses to images, local or remote. You can create flags just with some codes that

00:02:53.919 --> 00:03:03.119
you put in cells. There's really a lot you can do. We also made sure that gt allows for some

00:03:03.119 --> 00:03:08.960
methods for restructuring the table data. So initially, you do get a table coming in,

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:13.360
and it has a fixed form. But within gt, you can change it up a little bit. You could,

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:18.639
for instance, add spanners, and if columns are gathered under the same spanner,

00:03:18.639 --> 00:03:22.559
columns will move towards that spanner and be gathered together.

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:28.399
Also, you can just move columns around. There's actually functions just for that. In case you

00:03:28.399 --> 00:03:32.080
just change your mind, you don't want to go back up to the dplyr or whatever code,

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:39.199
you can just do within gt. Another big thing that gt does that's pretty great is footnotes.

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:45.360
It's pretty straightforward to define footnotes. You just use a function tab footnote.

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:52.559
gt takes care of the ordering and the lettering or numbering of that. And you can modify the

00:03:52.559 --> 00:03:58.479
spine details in terms of letters or numbers or whatever symbols you want to use. And the cool

00:03:58.479 --> 00:04:04.800
thing is it does things that you expect from publishing. It will reuse the same footnote

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:09.199
multiple times and apply the same mark. Or if there's multiple footnotes at the same location,

00:04:09.199 --> 00:04:14.720
it will intelligently create the footnote marks in the right way and the right order.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.720
Okay. As I said, 2023 has been pretty big for gt. There's two releases this year,

00:04:23.679 --> 00:04:29.839
0.9 and 0.10. I'll give you the main features of each because we only have a little bit of time.

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:35.679
In 0.9, which came out late March of this year, we added interactive HTML tables.

00:04:36.559 --> 00:04:41.359
We added some functionality for splitting gt tables across pages, for instance, in a Word

00:04:41.359 --> 00:04:48.480
document, LaTeX, or RTF. And we also enhanced one function called calls merge to better handle

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:55.519
any values and columns. And I'll go through this in a bit. Also, in 0.10, we introduced

00:04:55.519 --> 00:05:00.880
something called nanoplots, which are little tiny interactive plots, for now, just for HTML output

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:05.920
tables. We have something called units notation. It allows you to express measurement units easily

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:12.399
and they work across all output formats with one type of notation. And we also included more

00:05:12.399 --> 00:05:17.440
dynamic formatting with the from column helper function. Okay. This will all be explained in

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:23.839
the next few slides. So, we'll start interactive tables. So, we have a table here. I just want to

00:05:23.839 --> 00:05:29.359
draw your attention to this function we use, opt interactive. What that does is it takes this table,

00:05:29.359 --> 00:05:35.040
makes it HTML, and then makes it interactive. So, we have things like controls for sorting,

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:40.559
pagination, and we still have the other features of gt, like the title and the source notes and

00:05:40.559 --> 00:05:46.239
footnotes, and we can do styling as well and all sorts of formatting. So, we have a little bit of

00:05:46.239 --> 00:05:54.399
interactivity and a lot of formatting and styling. The next thing is splitting tables across pages.

00:05:54.399 --> 00:06:00.320
So, we have a new function called gt split, and you can control splits at rows and or columns.

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:04.399
So, you can say every five rows, let's make a split, or you can do it at different indices,

00:06:04.399 --> 00:06:09.519
if you want to take a more manual approach to it. So, obviously, this is useful for paginated docs,

00:06:09.519 --> 00:06:17.040
like Word docs and RTFs, and it looks like this. So, now we have two tables. We split

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:23.040
across the fifth row, and the top one will be on page one. The bottom will be on page two.

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:26.720
Obviously, you probably want more rows than that, but you kind of see where this is going. You could

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:35.920
sort of, like, split at even intervals. Okay. And we have a calls merge function that's more

00:06:35.920 --> 00:06:40.320
powerful. You can handle any values now. So, it's a little hard to sort of parse, but we have these

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:45.359
double angled brackets, and that just means, like, any values in the second column mentioned in

00:06:45.359 --> 00:06:50.959
columns, if there's any NAs in here, this whole thing disappears. So, we can gracefully remove

00:06:50.959 --> 00:06:57.920
parts of the merging process. So, let's take a look at that in sort of, like, this little example

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:03.920
here. We see here this row Tesla. It doesn't have any value here. So, very gracefully, it doesn't

00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:10.000
show any in here with parentheses. It just shows 243. And this one doesn't have any, has NAs for

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.519
both of these values. So, it doesn't show anything, because the entire expression is handled with

00:07:15.519 --> 00:07:24.239
double angled brackets. So, nanoplots are a new thing as well. Again, this is just for HTML,

00:07:24.239 --> 00:07:28.799
because we don't have a static version of this yet, but they're interactive. They use SVG to

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:33.279
draw the little graphics, and I'll show you that. They're not going to be interactive here in this

00:07:33.279 --> 00:07:37.200
slide presentation, but I do invite you to take one of these examples, give it a spin,

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:42.959
throw it in a browser like this table, and hover over different points. And if you do,

00:07:42.959 --> 00:07:47.359
you'll see the little data points will show up, little markers and things like that.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:52.640
And they're pretty fun to use, and you can very much customize these. You can include the bottom

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:58.640
area. You can remove the line, change the type of the line, remove the dots, all sorts of things

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:05.920
you can do. Okay. And we've got one more thing, well, two more things. One is unit sortation,

00:08:06.559 --> 00:08:12.320
and the idea is it makes inserting measurement units easy. So, we have an example right here.

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:16.399
There's actually a few functions that use this. We kind of integrate this everywhere.

00:08:16.399 --> 00:08:20.880
But if you use this type of formatting, where you use things like exponents, like with this

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:26.640
caret, and then minus one, or we use a little bit of markdown, and there's many other sort of

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:33.679
niceties in here, you can create units that just affix to column labels. You can just attach them

00:08:33.679 --> 00:08:39.440
to the column labels with another syntax. You can have them in a column, for instance, and use

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:43.919
format units. And it's really quite nice. It does a lot of sort of things which are kind of a pain

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:50.479
to do, and you have to resort to pretty bad methods to make this work. But I'm hoping this, it handles

00:08:50.479 --> 00:08:59.520
a lot of units cases. Okay. And one more thing I want to get to is this new from column helper

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:07.119
function. So, this is a bit like ggplot, where you can take values from a column and they affect

00:09:07.119 --> 00:09:13.119
the formatting or the aesthetics. So, in this case, we have certain functions that handle or allow

00:09:13.119 --> 00:09:18.159
from column in certain parameters. In this case, we have format scientific, and you might imagine a

00:09:18.159 --> 00:09:23.599
case where you don't want the significant digits to be the same across all cells. You want them to

00:09:23.599 --> 00:09:29.039
vary. So, you may have another column which has those values. And then typically what we do is

00:09:29.039 --> 00:09:34.719
we hide those columns that contain those work values. So, we can sort of see here that this

00:09:34.719 --> 00:09:40.479
Mulder-Planck constant has a lot of significant digits, whereas these other ones, like Planck-Moss,

00:09:40.479 --> 00:09:46.719
have less. And that's all because of from column. This allows you to sort of like fine-tune and,

00:09:46.719 --> 00:09:55.520
you know, make these correct, in other words. And this is all I have about GT this year. There's a

00:09:55.520 --> 00:09:59.760
lot of features. I just want to cover a few in this 10-minute talk. If you want to find out more,

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:06.320
go to GitHub slash RStudio slash GT. You can even take a test drive on Paws of Cloud. There's a

00:10:06.320 --> 00:10:11.280
whole bunch of examples in there. And otherwise, you can go to the reference section, just explore.

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:15.919
There's lots of examples in there and format output. You can copy and paste when you have

00:10:15.919 --> 00:10:22.799
GT installed. It's really quite nice. And this presentation is available on my personal GitHub,

00:10:22.799 --> 00:10:29.200
github.com, rich-enin slash presentations. Thank you.

